Hi!!! 

Yes, we are a Deaf family! Yes, it could be heredity. 

We are happy to have you here! I know you have a lot of questions and are curious about us. Drop some comments and we will answer! 

 🤟🏽

hi 🤍 

we wanted to reintroduce ourselves since we have many new followers here. 

Yes, we are a Deaf family and use American Sign Language to communicate with each other. 

Our two kids, Everlyn (deaf), and Jabez (hard of hearing), were born with deafness from my genes since I have two Deaf brothers in my whole family. 

My husband, Oscar, does not carry deaf gene because he was born hearing until he got hearing loss at 3-5 years old due to severe sickness. 

Being Deaf doesn’t mean they will pass deafness to their children. 90 percent of deaf children are born to hearing parents. As Deaf parents, we are part of the 10 percent.

we are passionate to share Deaf awareness with deaf kids. they have so many abilities, especially when they learn sign language. we are here to show hearing parents that deaf babies don't need to be "fixed". we are here to show you that deaf kids can do anything. they can do many "firsts" if you show them the love and patient and be part of their growth. also learn the language to help them be free to express themselves. i have the passion to show you the tools i use to teach my kids and also our journey as a Deaf family with Deaf kids

just know that im no expert in language development or speech development. I am sharing our experiences with Deaf kids and how they response to the tools we use to help them grow 🤍🤟🏽

Wow, 200K followers. Never thought this was possible that we’d hit that number, but here we are! We are absolutely blown away by the support and love from you all!! Anyways, we decided not to homeschool her because she loves school so much so she’ll be in mainstream class with her other deaf friends and a sign language interpreter in upcoming school year. 💓

It’s too cute not to share! For those who are asking if my parents are deaf, they are not. They are hearing. My dad is still learning ASL. My mom knows ASL, but still learning. I don’t know why I’m saying this, but I’m so glad they have deaf grandchildren because it forces them to continue learning ASL for them 😂

Common people usually say “no sign language” to deaf and hard of hearing children because they often believe that teaching sign language might hinder the child’s ability to learn spoken language or integrate into the hearing world. However, this approach is outdated and not recommended. It’s essential to expose deaf children to sign language as it can help them develop crucial communication skills and foster their cognitive and emotional development. Moreover, sign language provides a means for deaf children to connect with their deaf community and culture 🤟🏽❤️ #aslrocks #signlanguage

Throwback to my family. ❤️

Since you’re curious to learn about my dad Chava’s background, I’ll share a few things about him briefly. He’s not Deaf, and he doesn’t use ASL; mostly home signs. Both my parents have not been together since I was a little girl, and my dad was not around every day to be able to learn more signs. That’s why we still have communication barriers. But he has always been there for me when I need him. And yes, I am saddened to know that he’s leaving, but at the same time, I’m happy, knowing that he will be happier back in Mexico with his siblings and their families. We will definitely visit him when we can.

For those who asked me questions from my stories, I will post YouTube videos and reels answering those questions. Right now, we am spending as much time as we can with chava before he leaves tomorrow.

Sending heartfelt farewells as my father embarks on his journey back to Mexico. Until we meet again, dad! 🌟💔💞

The initial experience of homeschooling my kindergartener was a mix of excitement and a touch of nervousness. Having her with me every day is incredibly rewarding and a true blessing, as it allows me to gain a deeper understanding of her unique personality.

I hesitated to share this because I haven’t fully prepared myself to address the many questions related to her social and language skills, especially since she is Deaf. Exploring Deaf and Hard of Hearing curriculums and homeschooling resources is a new journey for me as a first-time homeschooling parent. I’m still in the process of discovering the right curriculum and resources tailored to the needs of deaf students. As my homeschooling journey begins, I’m eager to learn more about homeschooling with deaf children. If you have information about DHH curriculums, events, or anything else related to this, please share it with me! Thank you for being a part of our journey! 

ps: I’m using “The Good and the Beautiful” curriculum for kindergarten math. @thegoodandthebeautiful
Join me as I navigate the path of homeschooling as a parent. ✨🩷

I almost forgot that today is the start of Hispanic Heritage Month! I want to share that our family is primarily Deaf, but we’re also proud of our Latino roots. We’ve mostly concentrated on promoting sign language awareness for deaf children, often leaving less time to celebrate our Latino culture. This choice reflects the challenges we face in our daily lives as Deaf individuals. We’ll make an effort to share more about our Latinx heritage and the unique challenges it has brought into our lives as we continue on our journey. 🇲🇽🇺🇸🤟🏽

If you're new here, welcome! We're a Latinx family who are deaf, and both of us, @that.deaf.dad and I, as deaf parents, are the first generation of deafness in our families. We're also the first generation born in America from immigrant families 🇲🇽 . We're here to spread awareness about the importance of providing deaf and hard of hearing children access to a natural language through sign language. Regardless of whether they use hearing devices or choose to communicate verbally, having sign language in their lives ensures they can live and thrive more easily. We communicate using American Sign Language and read/write English as our second language. I'm currently homeschooling my daughter in kindergarten, and we're enjoying learning together in math, language arts, and crafting activities! My son, Jabez, who loves reading books 📚💕

Deaf and hard of hearing children can learn English as their second language. It’s important for them to have a first language, like sign language, which helps them communicate, ask questions, and express their understanding or confusion while they start learning another language. #homeschooling

As you know, I homeschooled my daughter for the first time this year. At the beginning, I had a mix of feelings, unsure whether my decision to homeschool was right. I had thoughts of ‘what ifs’—what if I go wrong in raising my deaf child, or should I put her into public school? In the end, both of us are enjoying homeschooling because it’s so flexible with our schedules, and we’re able to learn things that traditional school hasn’t taught. I realized that it’s okay to try new things even if you’re unsure. Why not give it a try and see how amazing your relationship with your child can become? #homeschool

Please do not take my advice on anxiety causing eye muscle weakness without consulting with your doctor first. 🙏🏽

I was diagnosed with severe anxiety by doctors last year, and I struggled to accept the diagnosis. As a mother, I don’t want my kids to know that I have anxiety because anxiety is no joke at all; it makes me feel overwhelmed. One day, I decided to run to God alone in my little office and surrendered to Him. He filled me with His promises, and I felt like I’m on cloud nine. Day by day, I run to Him, and afterwards, I finally feel normal. It is because of Him!

The question I often ask is, “At what age should I request a sign language interpreter for my deaf or HoH child?” I would say, start now, no matter their age. Both of my deaf and HoH kids have been using a sign language interpreter since they were babies! Of course, as a deaf parent, I always request an interpreter for myself, but it’s important to have my dhh children around to experience what it’s like to have an interpreter. 

If you live in the USA and have medical or private insurance, any office is required to provide an interpreter for your upcoming appointment after you request it. In my experience, medical or insurance covers it for you.
